\section{Introduction}


Patterns are spatially organized structures in nature that arise from the aggregation of elements in many different processes \cite{Fehsenfeld,Kawczynski,Vanag,Barthelemy,Fuentes,Anna}. Experiments and theory have shown that patterns are related to spatiotemporal nonlinear dynamics equations where specific structures can undergo nucleation \cite{Oliveira96,Gonzalez99}, aggregation, clustering, complex self-cooperative mechanisms, morphological changes, and complex biological variations \cite{Cross,Kenah,Newman,Pamplona,Colombo,Zhabotinsky,Legawiec,Fuentes2,Showalter,Jefferson,Jefferson11}, to mention just a few. The inclusion of non-local interactions to study pattern formation has been of significant importance in the explanation of the interaction among neurons, granular systems, and population models with complex interactions such as predator-prey interactions \cite{Wakano,Murray,Malchow,Kosinski,Biham,Szabo,Keshet}. Non-locality in space has been implemented through integro-differential reaction-diffusion equations in many physical systems. For example, intercellular nutrients and their interactions can be described as non-local reaction diffusion effects in which patterns arise when the activator and inhibitor are present non-uniformly in space. Moreover, non-local reaction diffusion models have been largely studied in the context of the formation of traveling waves \cite{Hildebrand}, in the dynamics of fronts and defects \cite{Nicola}, in chemical interactions and in Hopf bifurcation \cite{Rovinsky}.

In this study, we propose a general extension of the population Fisher equation, where the growth and interaction terms are generalized to describe nonlocal interactions in space. The nonlocal differential equation is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{interaction_competition}
\frac{\partial u(x,t)}{\partial t}=a\int_{\Omega}g_{\alpha}(x-x')u(x',t)dx'
-bu(x,t)\int_{\Omega}h_{\beta}(x-x')u(x',t)dx'\,\,,
\end{eqnarray}






where the parameters growth $a$ and competition $b$ are general constants of the model. The kernels $g_{\alpha}(x-x')$ and $h_{\beta}(x-x')$ are the nonlocal correlations for the growth and competition terms, respectively, which weight the interaction among the individuals of the system. The key feature here is that the nonlocal correlations are controlled by parameters $\alpha$ and $\beta$ which refer respectively to the growth and interaction lengths. Note that this allows us to relate the effects of non-locality of growth and interaction using only the lengths $\alpha$ and $\beta$. Note also that Eq.~(\ref{interaction_competition}) incorporates the classical logistic equation $\partial u(x,t)/\partial t = au(x,t)-bu^{2}(x,t)$ when we take the kernels $h_{\beta}(x-x')=g_{\alpha}(x-x')=\delta(x-x')$ as a delta function. Moreover, another important feature is that the nonlocal growth integral in Eq.~(\ref{interaction_competition}) concentrates, in a simple manner, typical growth, diffusion, and higher derivative orders related to the dispersive terms. Then all the properties of these terms are included in the model by varying only the lengths $\alpha$.

We study the stationary pattern solutions of Eq.~(\ref{interaction_competition}) analytically and numerically expressed in terms of the parameters $\alpha$ and $\beta$. Basically, we start to show that there are two types of possible solutions, which we denominate simply as wavelike and Gaussian pattern solutions. We show that these solutions enclose the properties of non-locality and nonlinearity of the system wherein analytical expressions are presented. These solutions allow us an overview of pattern formation process including a complete analysis of the pattern focused in the number of peaks as well as their pattern transitions when we vary $\alpha$ and $\beta$. Based on this, we analyze graphically and theoretically the relation between patterns, peaks, and their pattern transitions.


